          "body": "The chapter's most forensically devastating move is the direct quotation of the accused. God does not merely describe their behavior; He quotes their inner dialogue verbatim: 'When will the new moon be over, so that we may sell grain? And the Sabbath, that we may open the wheat market?' This is the anatomy of covetous religiosity — not atheism, not formal apostasy, but the use of religious calendar observance as a thin cover for commercial ambition. They keep the Sabbath in body while violating it in desire. Amos would have recognized in his audience the same phenomenon Ezekiel later named: 'They sit before you as My people and hear your words, but they do not do them; for with their mouth they show much love, but their heart goes after their covetousness' (Ezekiel 33:31). The specific frauds are commercial and systematic: smaller measures (less grain delivered than purchased), inflated prices (the shekel inflated beyond its standard weight), dishonest scales (the instrument of transaction itself bent). The combination means fraud at every level of the market — product, price, and process. Then the moral nadir: buying the helpless for money, the needy for a pair of sandals — debt slavery for the most trivial sums — and mixing chaff with clean grain to sell refuse as food to those too desperate to refuse. The Mosaic law had addressed each of these practices explicitly (Leviticus 19:35-36; Deuteronomy 25:13-16; Exodus 22:22-24); Israel is not sinning in ignorance."
